title: For Sale:  Remington Hepburn
postcontent: This is to settle an estate.  No trades are possible.  This is a nice old Remington Hepburn rifle Serial Number just over 8,000.  Only about 8 to 10 thousand total were made.  Many of those were later used for wildcat actions and an original configuration Hepburn is a prize to find.  The falling block action is very strong in these rifles.  The 28" octagon to round barrel is in caliber 38-55 Winchester. The muzzle has been crowned. Brass and dies ar readily available to shoot it.  There is an good quality though unmarked mid range rear vernier tang sight, and a very good quality though unmarked front globe type, changeable insert, sight adjustable for windage with a spirit level.  The gun is turning a pleasing plum color, wood is sound, the action is good.  The forearm has the ebony insert, and the wrist is checkered.  The bore is poor and although it shoots, it would be a good candidate for a barrel liner.  That is easily done in a home shop with a minimum of tools and skill.  The barrel address is correct.  All in all a decent collector, and potentially great shooter.

title: For Sale:  Stevens 44 1/2 .32-40 Win
postcontent: This sale is to settle an estate.  Trades are not possible.  This listing is for a nice old Stevens Model 44 1/2 (Ideal) in caliber .32-40 Winchester.  The falling block action in these guns is strong enough for modern ammunition and 32-40 brass and dies are readily available.  The barrel is 27 3/4" long and like rest of the gun is a pleasing silver to brown color.  Very little case color remains.  The barrel has been crowned.  The action is tight.  The wood is solid with decent finish but has a few old gouges and marks you would expect after a hundred years.  It has a good bore.  The barrel has been drilled and tapped for Unertl style mounts and those holes have filler screws in them.  The tang is drilled and tapped for a vernier sight but none is present.  The front sight appears to be a Lyman 17A globe type sight with changeable inserts.  The barrel is octagon to round.  The is a small rather odd rear barrel sight in place that I THINK may have come off a lower grade Stevens such as the Favorite, CrackShot, Marksman etc, but while functional is not correct for the gun.  All in all this is a good functional rifle that carries great nostalgia for someone looking to simply hunt or target shoot with it.

title: For Sale:  1885 Winchester High Wall
postcontent: This is to settle an estate.  Trades are not possible.  This auction is for a great summer project.  The receiver and barrel are from a Winchester Model 1885 Single Shot High Wall.  The original caliber was .38-55 Winchester.  There are NO GUTS at all in the receiver.  The barrel is intact, 30" long, carries what appears to be the original front sight and a replacement rear sight.  The receiver is Serial 3362X which dates the gun to 1889.  It is a flat mainspring type action.  The butt stock appears to have been bought at a later date apparently for $15 and is probably from a Uberti.  The bright blue buttplate is in place and the buttstock trap is present.  It has been fit to the receiver.  The original forearm is present, has the ebony insert, and is held in place with a pipe cleaner that is probably a later addition to the gun.  These guns are great shooters when completed.  It will probably require a barrel liner.  This is easily done in a home shop with a minimum of tools and skills.  Parts for these guns are readily available on eBay and other sights.

postcontent: I have a fantastic Model 1897 Winchester Take Down Version Slide (Pump) Action Repeater 12 Gauge Shotgun. This beauty from 1934 is in good to excellent condition. It has some faded bluing that just adds to the character of this gem from the past. It obviously has been used for hunting and has been meticulously cared for. $40.00 meant something during The Great Depression. The stock and forearm are both in near-perfect condition. The original hard rubber butt plate has some cracks and chips, as you can see from the picture. I would guess this has been from some rabbit and squirrel head crackin'. If you are truly a hunter, you know what I mean...It is said that the Germans in WW1 complained about this weapon's evil twin, the trench version, that was surely a violation of the Hague Convention as it was devastating to them in trench warfare. It is also rumored that our US boys had been used to bird hunting with this shotgun and would shoot grenades being lobbed at them, either blowing up the grenades or at the very least, knocking them off course...
